{
  "texts": [
    "In the standard setting, the agent learns from stochastic feedback in the form of real-valued rewards.",
    "In many applications, however, numerical reward signals are not readily available-instead, only weaker information is provided, in particular relative preferences in the form of qualitative comparisons between pairs of alternatives.",
    "This observation has motivated the study of variants of the multi-armed bandit problem, in which more general representations are used both for the type of feedback to learn from and the target of prediction.",
    "The dueling bandits problem (Yue and Joachims 2009) describes an online learning scenario, in which the observed feedback consists of comparative preference information.",
    "In its basic form, there are m choice alternatives (options) a 1,."
  ]
}